Analyzing plate reader and growth data

For analyzing growth data in R, you need two things.

  1. To create a “mapping file”. This means a file that tells R what was in what well
  2. To read in the raw data you get off the plate reader

Mapping file and plate map

Let’s see a mapping file first. You can make this in excel or in R. Erica’s plate is really complicated and is a combination of

  • two different carbon sources (glucose and glycerol)
  • two different strains (code named 1 and 10)
  • two different amendments (lysine and a lysine alternative)
  • at two different concentrations (0.05 mM and 0.125 mM).

Her plate map looks like this:

The mapping file needs to contain all of this information. Here’s what the one I made looks like:

wells conditions media strain condition_only concentration
A1 Alt_0.05 glucose 1 Alt 0.05
A2 Alt_0.05 glucose 1 Alt 0.05
A3 Alt_0.05 glucose 1 Alt 0.05
A4 Lys_0.05 glucose 1 Lys 0.05
A5 Lys_0.05 glucose 1 Lys 0.05
A6 Lys_0.05 glucose 1 Lys 0.05

Now we can move on to loading the plate reader data.

Loading in clariostar data

Erica has clariostar data. We have the raw excel file that clariostar spits out. There’s a library in R (readxl) that can read excel files directly, but we have to tell it the range of excel columns and rows that we want. We only want the actual measurements, not the 5000 lines of metadata that clariostar spits out. First let’s open the excel file and look at what we’re dealing with.

In this case we want the range B11:CT112. Let’s load it and take a look!

od <- read_excel('../data/erica_4.10.24_clariostar_data.xlsx', range = 'B11:CT112')
pretty_table(head(od[,1:4]))

What we loaded in is tragically ugly and quite messy. We need to do further processing before we can use it.

First we can remove the first row in the dataframe. This is just sample names, which no one (?) uses anyway.

od <- od[-1,]
pretty_table(head(od[,1:4]))
…1 A01 A02 A03
0 h 0.28100000000000003 0.247 0.28299999999999997
0 h 30 min 0.28299999999999997 0.25800000000000001 0.27600000000000002
1 h 0.28000000000000003 0.27100000000000002 0.27600000000000002
1 h 30 min 0.27200000000000002 0.28899999999999998 0.27400000000000002
2 h 0.26900000000000002 0.28799999999999998 0.27300000000000002
2 h 30 min 0.27 0.28599999999999998 0.27600000000000002

Looking better! Now we need to put the time into units R can use. 0h 30 min is not useful for plotting. Here we’ll do this using seq. Seq generates numbers from whatever to whatever by whatever increment. We want it to go from 0 to the last measurement, increasing by 30 each time. We can find what the final measurement should be by taking the number of rows nrow(od) of the data we loaded in, subtract that by one and multiply this number by the time interval. In R speak that equals (nrow(od) - 1) * 30

seq(from = 0, to = (nrow(od) - 1) * 30, by = 30)
##   [1]    0   30   60   90  120  150  180  210  240  270  300  330  360  390  420
##  [16]  450  480  510  540  570  600  630  660  690  720  750  780  810  840  870
##  [31]  900  930  960  990 1020 1050 1080 1110 1140 1170 1200 1230 1260 1290 1320
##  [46] 1350 1380 1410 1440 1470 1500 1530 1560 1590 1620 1650 1680 1710 1740 1770
##  [61] 1800 1830 1860 1890 1920 1950 1980 2010 2040 2070 2100 2130 2160 2190 2220
##  [76] 2250 2280 2310 2340 2370 2400 2430 2460 2490 2520 2550 2580 2610 2640 2670
##  [91] 2700 2730 2760 2790 2820 2850 2880 2910 2940 2970
od$time <- seq(from = 0, to = (nrow(od) - 1) * 30, by = 30)
od <- od[,-1] #remove the time column clariostar gave us

Now that we have the time fixed we just need to do a little housekeeping. First off change our data into long format. I like to do this with the reshape2 library, and specifically the melt function. Then we’ll fix a couple other loose ends.

#reshape and rename columns
od <- melt(od, id.vars = 'time')
colnames(od)[2:3] <- c('wells', 'value')

#fix well discrepancy
od$wells <- gsub('([[:alpha:]])0', '\\1', od$wells) 
#replace any well that has a letter followed by a number by just the letter
#just turns A01 -> A1 so we can use it as a key with the mapping file

#convert od values to numeric, they were read in as characters
od$value <- as.numeric(od$value)

#add the mapping info to the od measurements
od$cond <- mapping$conditions[match(od$wells, mapping$wells)]
od$media <- mapping$media[match(od$wells, mapping$wells)]
od$strain <- mapping$strain[match(od$wells, mapping$wells)]

#some wells were empty (rows G and H), but the plate-reader took measurements for them. 
#so they have NA for all the columns we transferred from the mapping file
pretty_table(head(subset(od, grepl('G', wells))))
time wells value cond media strain
7201 0 G1 0.231 NA NA NA
7202 30 G1 0.243 NA NA NA
7203 60 G1 0.242 NA NA NA
7204 90 G1 0.241 NA NA NA
7205 120 G1 0.242 NA NA NA
7206 150 G1 0.242 NA NA NA 
#this gets rid of them
od <- na.omit(od)

pretty_table(head(od))
time wells value cond media strain

Yeaaaah looks good! Now we can actually start to analyze our data.

Analyzing blanks

Erica likes complex things so there are eight different types of blanks.

blanks <- subset(od, strain == 'blank')
pretty_table(table(blanks$cond, blanks$media))
glucose glycerol
Alt_blank 100 100
blank 300 300
Lys_blank 100 100
no_aa 100 100

Let’s see what everything looks like first by faceting across the media type and strains.

ggplot(od, aes(x = time, y = value)) +
  facet_grid(strain~media) +
  geom_smooth(aes(group = wells, color = cond), linewidth = 1.1, se = F) +
  xlab("Time (minutes)") +
  ylab("OD 600") +
  scale_y_log10() +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = 'Set3') +
  theme_classic(base_size = 18, base_family = 'Helvetica')

We can see the blanks aren’t really too different from each other, and none are contaminated. Good job Erica! However they do decrease over time due to evaporation. For these exercises I’ll just average them together across each time point, then subtract these values from the experimental wells. Then we can get rid of the blanks.

blank_vals <- aggregate(value ~ time, data = blanks, FUN = mean)
od$blank_avg <- blank_vals$value[match(od$time, blank_vals$time)]

od$corrected_od <- od$value - od$blank_avg
od <- subset(od, strain != 'blank')
rm(blanks, blank_vals)

pretty_table(head(od))
time wells value cond media strain blank_avg corrected_od

30 A1 0.283 Alt_0.05 glucose 1 0.2392500 0.0437500
60 A1 0.280 Alt_0.05 glucose 1 0.2391667 0.0408333

Analyzing and plotting data

Now we can actually get to the fun part, looking at the data and picking whatever weird colors we want.

colorz <- c("#BBECCD", "#7fdba1", "#ad85cf", "#884eb9", "black")

#let's take a look
ggplot(od, aes(x = time, y = corrected_od)) +
  facet_grid(strain~media) +
  geom_smooth(aes(group = wells, color = cond), linewidth = 1.1, se = F) +
  xlab("Time (seconds)") +
  ylab("OD 600") +
  scale_color_manual(values = colorz, name = 'Conditions') +
  scale_y_log10() +
  theme_classic(base_size = 18, base_family = 'Helvetica')

Alright, so we can see the no amino acid wells basically didn’t grow. Checks out. Let’s remove them from further analysis.

od <- subset(od, cond != 'no_aa')

ggplot(od, aes(x = time, y = corrected_od)) +
  facet_grid(cond~media, scales = 'free_y') +
  geom_smooth(aes(group = wells, color = strain), linewidth = 1.1, se = F) +
  xlab("Time (seconds)") +
  ylab("OD 600") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#BBECCD", "#ad85cf")) +
  scale_y_log10() +
  theme_classic(base_size = 18, base_family = 'Helvetica')

We can see that the replicates look very similar. Let’s combine then and make error bars.

#get mean value for line
mean_val <- aggregate(corrected_od ~ time * paste(cond, media, strain, sep = '_'), data =  od, FUN = mean)
colnames(mean_val)[2] <- c('name')

#get sd for error bars
mean_sd <- aggregate(corrected_od ~ time * paste(cond, media, strain, sep = '_'), od, sd)
colnames(mean_sd)[2] <- c('name')
mean_val$sd <- mean_sd$corrected_od[match(mean_val$name, mean_sd$name)]

#separate out variables
mean_val$media <- str_split_fixed(mean_val$name, '_', 4)[,3] 
mean_val$strain <- str_split_fixed(mean_val$name, '_', 4)[,4] 
mean_val$cond <- str_split_fixed(mean_val$name, '_', 4)[,1] 
mean_val$conc <- str_split_fixed(mean_val$name, '_', 4)[,2] 
rm(mean_sd)

ggplot(mean_val, aes(x = time, y = corrected_od)) +
  facet_grid(cond~media, scales = 'free') +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = corrected_od - sd, 
                    ymax = corrected_od + sd, color = paste(strain, conc)),
                width = 0.2, position = position_dodge(width = 0.9), alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_line(aes(group = name, color = paste(strain, conc)), linewidth = 1.1, se = F) +
  xlab("Time (seconds)") +
  ylab("OD 600") +
  scale_color_manual(values = colorz, name = 'Strain / concentration', 
                     labels = c('1, 0.05 mM', '1, 0.125 mM', 
                                '10, 0.05 mM', '10, 0.125 mM')) +
  scale_y_log10() + 
  theme_classic(base_size = 18, base_family = 'Helvetica')

Calculating growth rates using growthcurver

R has a nice package (growthcurver) for calculating growth rates from plate reader data using the function SummarizeGrowthByPlate. If you plan to use it, I recommend checking out their tutorial, found here.

To use growthcurver we need our data to be back in wide format (each well as a column). We can do this using dcast

#Growthcurver needs time in one column, then one column for each well (wide format)
growth_data <- dcast(od, time ~ wells, value.var = 'corrected_od')
growth_data$time <- growth_data$time / 60 #expects hours, not minutes according to help file
pretty_table(head(growth_data[, 1:5]))
time A1 A10 A11 A12
0.0 0.0426667 0.0006667 -0.0023333 -0.0153333
0.5 0.0437500 -0.0012500 0.0007500 0.0037500
1.0 0.0408333 -0.0041667 0.0008333 0.0068333
1.5 0.0325833 -0.0034167 0.0025833 0.0075833
2.0 0.0300000 0.0010000 0.0050000 0.0120000
2.5 0.0310833 0.0050833 0.0130833 0.0140833

Now we’re ready to actually run the function to calculate growth rate for each of our wells.

growth_curve <- SummarizeGrowthByPlate(growth_data)
pretty_table(head(growth_curve))

Growthcurver spits out a lot of information, but for our purposes we’re interested in the t_gen (doubling time). It’s very important to look at the note column as well - if the function couldn’t calculate doubling time or had any difficulties you’ll find warnings there.

mapping$t_gen <- growth_curve$t_gen[match(mapping$well, growth_curve$sample)]

growth_plot <- subset(mapping, strain != 'blank' & conditions != 'no_aa')

#plot generation time versus metrics
ggplot(growth_plot, aes(x = concentration, y = t_gen, fill = strain)) +
  facet_grid(media ~ condition_only, scales = 'free_y') +
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.5, outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_point(size = 3, pch = 21, position = position_jitterdodge()) +
  ylab('Generation time (hours)') +
  xlab(expression(paste('Concentration (mM)'))) +
  theme_classic(base_size = 18, base_family = 'Helvetica') +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#BBECCD", "#ad85cf"))

Alright, looks like strain 10 grows much better on the lysine alternative than strain 1. But is it a significant difference? Let’s seeeee.

Calculating significance

Using the R package ggsignif we can calculate significance with a t-test directly on our plots. For convenience, I’ll split up the glucose and glycerol results.

growth_plot$label <- paste(growth_plot$condition_only, ' ', growth_plot$concentration, ' mM', sep = '')
#making a nice label with mu using unicode characters

ggplot(subset(growth_plot, media == 'glucose'), aes(x = as.character(strain), y = t_gen, fill = strain)) +
  facet_wrap(~label, nrow = 1) +
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.5, outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_signif(comparisons = list(c('1', '10')), test = 't.test', y_position = 10.5, 
              tip_length = 0, family = 'Helvetica') +
  geom_point(size = 3, pch = 21, position = position_jitterdodge()) +
  ggtitle('Growth comparision on glucose') +
  ylab('Generation time (hours)') +
  ylim(c(0, 12)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#BBECCD", "#ad85cf")) +
  theme_classic(base_size = 18, base_family = 'Helvetica') +
  theme(axis.title.x=element_blank(),
        axis.text.x=element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.x=element_blank())

ggplot(subset(growth_plot, media == 'glycerol'), aes(x = as.character(strain), y = t_gen, fill = strain)) +
  facet_grid(~label) +
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.5, outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_signif(comparisons = list(c('1', '10')), test = 't.test', y_position = 3.75, 
              tip_length = 0, family = 'Helvetica') +
  geom_point(size = 3, pch = 21, position = position_jitterdodge()) +
  ggtitle('Growth comparision on glycerol') +
  ylab('Generation time (hours)') +
  ylim(c(0, 4.25)) +
  theme_classic(base_size = 18, base_family = 'Helvetica') +
  theme(axis.title.x=element_blank(),
        axis.text.x=element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.x=element_blank()) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#BBECCD", "#ad85cf"))

Okay, so we can see that differences in growth rates between the strains are only significant (with the lysine alternative) when the media contains glycerol as the carbon source. Is that interesting scientifically? I don’t know, ask Erica!
